supportDesc.foliation: No foliation; digital locus markers supplied.

p.note: Top left corner: National Library book label with the current signum; top of page, in black ink by a modern hand: a note on the origin and accession of the manuscript, Fragmenter af ett Psalterium skrifvet i Sverige och begagnadt i en landskyrka i Uppland möjligtvis i Sigtuna In köpt på Hyckerströms auktion i Uppsala 23/3 1855 för 16 sk No 3.
Edge of pastedown, a partially damaged note in a contemporary hand: anno domini MC Consilia nostri initium (?).

binding.p: Brown leather over bevelled wooden boards. 5 double raised bands and endbands. Originally pin clasps and straps.
binding.condition: The manuscript is severely affected by water damage. The cover and pastedowns are worn; the binding is completely detached from the textblock and stored separately. Pin clasps and straps missing.

history.origin: According to a note on , the manuscript was written in Sweden . The script and mise-en-page date the manuscript to the 12th century, last quarter, or 13th century, first quarter, approximately.
history.provenance: According to the note on , the Psalter was used in a country church in Uppland, possibly at Sigtuna.
history.acquisition: Bought at auction at P. J. Hyckerström's in Uppsala in (see note on LCI).

note.p: : 51:5-11 followed by antiphons, psalms, a hymn, and an invitatory;
Antiphons for the psalms with musical notation throughout.

has been bound in the wrong place; it should follow after . In addition to this, the original scribe has, due to homoeoteleuton, skipped from Ps. 105:16 to 105:32; contains the missing section in the same hand.

supportDesc.condition: The textblock is severely damaged by water, with the first couple of folios barely legible, and the majority of the leaves, including the beginning and the end of the text, are missing. The remaining leaves are mounted on and/or repaired with modern paper. On (Ps. 101), a large initial has been cut out.

p.note: Bottom of every few leaves: National Library stamp.
Intermittently, on repair strip or in margin: the psalm number, and sometimes also the verse, in pencil in a modern hand.
Additions of omitted verses in the margin written in a triangular shape in a contemporary hand (possibly the main scribe) with an outline and signes-de-renvoi in red.
Corrections of the text in a contemporary hand.

physDesc.musicNotation: Staves of four lines in red with square notation.

decoDesc.p: Main text in black ink; rubrics in red; capitals alternating in red and green (on the inserted , red only).
decoDesc.decoNote: : plain initials over 2 lines alternating in red and green with flourishing in the contrasting colour, and some with interior reserved shapes.
